NEW YORK UNIVERSITY     ARTS AND SCIENCE     COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE     GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE                                Home       People       Undergraduate Program       Graduate Program       Alumni       Events       News       IR@NYU       Contact Us       Employment             Stay Connected           Facebook                    Back to Home               John Fousek       Visiting Associate Professor of International Relations         Office Address:   19 University Pl, Rm 527   New York, NY 10003   Email:     john.fousek@nyu.edu            Bio:      John Fousek joined NYU’s MA Program in International  Relations in 2013. He teaches graduate courses on global and international  history, the United States as a global power, and the intersection of culture  and international relations. Professor Fousek represents the MA Program on the  NYU Faculty of Arts and Science Working Group on International Studies. He has  taught previously at Yeshiva University, Rutgers University-Newark, Franklin  and Marshall College and Cornell University. He’s also held administrative  posts as associate director of the Center for Global Change and Governance at  Rutgers-Newark, program director of the Center for Ethics at Yeshiva  University, and executive director of a non-profit research and educational  organization, the World Order Models Project. He holds a bachelor’s degree from  Columbia University and a doctorate from Cornell.     Professor Fousek’s research and teaching interests focus on  the history of U.S. foreign relations from the colonial era to the present,  public opinion and the cultural construction of foreign policy, the Cold War  and its legacy, and the dynamics of world order in the post-Soviet era (before  and after Sept. 11, 2001). His book, To  Lead the Free World: American Nationalism and the Cultural Roots of the Cold  War (University of North Carolina Press), has been in press continuously  since its publication in 2000. He is co-editor of a collection of essays on Ethics  and the U.S. Presidency (Special Issue, Presidential  Studies Quarterly, March 2010). He has written on terrorism, political  ethics and the prevention of genocide as well as culture and U.S. foreign  policy.     Professor Fousek’s current projects include: a re-thinking  of the “American Century” narrative through an examination of the global impact  of Louis Armstrong and African-American music; an analysis of U.S. foreign  policy and American nationalism in relation to the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles;  and an ongoing assessment of discourses on “American exceptionalism” and  “isolationism” in U.S. foreign policy debates. NEW YORK UNIVERSITY     ARTS AND SCIENCE     COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE     GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE                                Home       People       Undergraduate Program       Graduate Program       Alumni       Events       News       IR@NYU       Contact Us       Employment             Stay Connected           Facebook                    Back to Home               John Fousek       Visiting Associate Professor of International Relations         Office Address:   19 University Pl, Rm 527   New York, NY 10003   Email:     john.fousek@nyu.edu            Bio:      John Fousek joined NYU’s MA Program in International  Relations in 2013. He teaches graduate courses on global and international  history, the United States as a global power, and the intersection of culture  and international relations. Professor Fousek represents the MA Program on the  NYU Faculty of Arts and Science Working Group on International Studies. He has  taught previously at Yeshiva University, Rutgers University-Newark, Franklin  and Marshall College and Cornell University. He’s also held administrative  posts as associate director of the Center for Global Change and Governance at  Rutgers-Newark, program director of the Center for Ethics at Yeshiva  University, and executive director of a non-profit research and educational  organization, the World Order Models Project. He holds a bachelor’s degree from  Columbia University and a doctorate from Cornell.     Professor Fousek’s research and teaching interests focus on  the history of U.S. foreign relations from the colonial era to the present,  public opinion and the cultural construction of foreign policy, the Cold War  and its legacy, and the dynamics of world order in the post-Soviet era (before  and after Sept. 11, 2001). His book, To  Lead the Free World: American Nationalism and the Cultural Roots of the Cold  War (University of North Carolina Press), has been in press continuously  since its publication in 2000. He is co-editor of a collection of essays on Ethics  and the U.S. Presidency (Special Issue, Presidential  Studies Quarterly, March 2010). He has written on terrorism, political  ethics and the prevention of genocide as well as culture and U.S. foreign  policy.     Professor Fousek’s current projects include: a re-thinking  of the “American Century” narrative through an examination of the global impact  of Louis Armstrong and African-American music; an analysis of U.S. foreign  policy and American nationalism in relation to the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles;  and an ongoing assessment of discourses on “American exceptionalism” and  “isolationism” in U.S. foreign policy debates. The United States and the World: Foreign Policy and the 2014 Elections | NYU Wagner                                    Jump to navigation                                                             The United States and the World: Foreign Policy and the 2014 Elections   PADM-GP.4224, 1.5 points.       Courses         Description |    Syllabi |    Evaluations           The rise of China. Terrorism. Nuclear proliferation. Human rights. Global poverty. Climate Change. What role should military force play in foreign policy? Arguments over how to respond to these issues reflect debates about the appropriate role that the United States should play in the world -- debates that date back to the country's founding. Should the United States aspire to global dominance? Should or can the United States foster the creation of an international society founded upon international law and cooperation? These and other questions will be explored by examining competing views on the most critical foreign policy issues of the 21st century, issues that will redefine the relationship between the United States and the world.
